Before we calculate the rate we need to calculate the number of years between 1895 and 2016.

$$ \begin{aligned}
t&= 2016 - 1895 \\
 & = \boxed{121}
\end{aligned}$$

There are 121 years in which we need to evaluate to know the applied rate.

Know we want to know how much will the prize be worth for the year 2040 provided that it increases at the same rate it has been increasing. For this, we need to know for how many periods we need to evaluate the applied rate.

$$ \begin{aligned}
t&= 2040 - 2016 \\
 & = \boxed{24}
\end{aligned}$$

We need to account for 24 years in advance.

To calculate this value we are going to use the FV formula which is shown in step 3. 

$$ \begin{aligned}
FV &= \$1,800,000\cdot(1+0.0807)^{24} \\
&= \boxed{\$11,593,008.13}

\end{aligned}$$

If we assume that the prize keeps increasing at the same rate of 8.07%, for 2040 the prize will be of **$11,593,008.13**.
